1
00:01:06,933 --> 00:01:13,304
.

2
00:02:15,468 --> 00:02:16,867
I want you John Bayley.

3
00:02:18,104 --> 00:02:19,571
I want you!

4
00:02:35,088 --> 00:02:39,422
Edward Lanman was sitting in
his pleasant house in London

5
00:02:40,460 --> 00:02:46,695
The sun was shining
It was an early morning in June, not quite...

6
00:02:58,678 --> 00:02:59,736
Iris.

7
00:03:00,313 --> 00:03:01,746
Iris, wait for me.

8
00:03:02,382 --> 00:03:04,407
Just keep tight hold of me and it'll be all right.

9
00:03:05,385 --> 00:03:07,649
-You won't keep still.
-I can't keep still.

10
00:03:08,488 --> 00:03:10,353
I can't catch up with you.

11
00:03:15,762 --> 00:03:19,198
.

12
00:03:33,346 --> 00:03:36,975
-Iris, you've got bicycle oil on your ankle.
-I don't care, John.

13
00:03:39,812 --> 00:03:41,370
Those of you, our guests...

14
00:03:41,414 --> 00:03:43,041
... on whose magnificent generosity
we depend...

15
00:03:43,683 --> 00:03:45,810
...we really are most frightfully grateful...

16
00:03:46,886 --> 00:03:49,946
...will need no introduction to
one of our most distinguished graduates...

17
00:03:51,324 --> 00:03:54,623
... an honorary fellow, Dame Iris Murdoch.

18
00:03:55,762 --> 00:04:00,131
She's a noted philosopher as well as
author of some twenty-six novels.

19
00:04:00,767 --> 00:04:03,258
And we are honoured to have her with us today.

20
00:04:03,770 --> 00:04:07,433
As well as the distinguished
Warton Professor of Literature..

21
00:04:07,940 --> 00:04:10,238
...who has the great good fortune
of being married to her.

22
00:04:11,577 --> 00:04:13,272
I need say no more about her.

23
00:04:13,846 --> 00:04:14,904
For good wine needs no bush.

24
00:04:16,149 --> 00:04:18,447
But she will not mind comparison with...

25
00:04:19,585 --> 00:04:21,519
... say, a really fine vintage claret.

26
00:04:25,358 --> 00:04:28,953
... Dame Iris will speak to you
about the importance of education.

27
00:04:42,008 --> 00:04:46,308
Education doesn't make you happy.
And nor does freedom.

28
00:04:48,448 --> 00:04:52,441
We don't become happy
just because we're free -- if we are...

29
00:04:53,252 --> 00:04:55,277
... or because we've been educated, if we have.

30
00:04:56,422 --> 00:04:58,822
But because education may be the means...

31
00:04:59,759 --> 00:05:01,249
... by which we realise we are happy.

32
00:05:02,328 --> 00:05:03,693
It opens our eyes, our ears.

33
00:05:05,064 --> 00:05:06,895
Tells us where delights are lurking.

34
00:05:08,201 --> 00:05:10,829
Convinces us that there is only one freedom...

35
00:05:11,771 --> 00:05:13,261
... of any importance whatsoever.

36
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:15,605
That of the mind.

37
00:05:16,542 --> 00:05:18,305
And gives us the assurance,the confidence...

38
00:05:19,512 --> 00:05:23,107
...to walk the path our mind,
our educated mind offers.

39
00:05:27,086 --> 00:05:30,681
I shall tell him all my love.

40
00:05:31,357 --> 00:05:34,349
All my soul's adoration.

41
00:05:35,962 --> 00:05:38,487
And I think he will hear me.

42
00:05:39,332 --> 00:05:42,495
And will not say me nay.

43
00:05:43,870 --> 00:05:47,328
It is this that gives my soul.

44
00:05:48,007 --> 00:05:52,341
All it's joyous elation.

45
00:05:53,112 --> 00:05:57,208
As I hear the sweet larks sing.

46
00:05:57,917 --> 00:06:03,514
In the clear air of the day.

47
00:06:04,156 --> 00:06:05,145
Yes, of course there's something fishy...

48
00:06:05,591 --> 00:06:06,751
... about describing people's feelings.

49
00:06:07,727 --> 00:06:09,126
Try hard to beaccurate, but...

50
00:06:09,829 --> 00:06:11,763
... as soon as you start to define
such and such a feeling...

51
00:06:11,797 --> 00:06:12,786
... language let's you down.

52
00:06:13,099 --> 00:06:15,090
When we really speak the truth,
words are insufficient.

53
00:06:15,568 --> 00:06:20,335
Almost everything,
except things like "pass the gravy" ...

54
00:06:20,806 --> 00:06:23,604
... is a lie of a sort.
And that being the case, I shall shut up.

55
00:06:26,212 --> 00:06:28,237
And pass the gravy.

56
00:06:33,352 --> 00:06:34,341
But love, or at least unsatisfied love...

57
00:06:34,921 --> 00:06:36,047
... is concerned as much with understanding.

58
00:06:36,689 --> 00:06:37,951
And real love, extreme love...

59
00:06:39,025 --> 00:06:40,458
... once it's recognised
has stamp of the indubitable...

60
00:06:41,027 --> 00:06:42,551
Ah, John, may I call you, John, may I?

61
00:06:42,995 --> 00:06:44,019
Meet Miss Murdoch.

62
00:06:44,430 --> 00:06:45,419
Iris, my dear, John Bayley.

63
00:06:45,731 --> 00:06:47,562
One of the more promising young lecturers
in the English School.

64
00:06:47,967 --> 00:06:51,562
Though I caught him out over
Old English grammar, his weaker side I fear.

65
00:06:52,004 --> 00:06:54,336
A minor question of Anglo-Saxon syntax.

66
00:06:58,044 --> 00:06:59,033
Wine!

67
00:07:00,646 --> 00:07:02,011
I mean...

68
00:07:02,415 --> 00:07:03,541
... It went down the wrong way.

69
00:07:04,450 --> 00:07:06,850
Yes, I like that.

70
00:07:07,620 --> 00:07:09,144
There is a right way down, of course.

71
00:07:09,689 --> 00:07:11,782
Amazing how most of us find it
without even thinking about it.

72
00:07:12,458 --> 00:07:13,720
I rarely think...

73
00:07:14,360 --> 00:07:15,486
If you think about it, you'll never find it.

74
00:07:16,429 --> 00:07:17,828
Best thing to do
is hang on and trust the body. I do.

75
00:07:19,665 --> 00:07:20,791
Human beings love each other.

76
00:07:22,068 --> 00:07:24,161
In sex, in friendship...

77
00:07:24,904 --> 00:07:26,462
... and when they're in love.

78
00:07:28,240 --> 00:07:30,071
And they cherish other beings.

79
00:07:30,810 --> 00:07:34,644
Humans, animals, plants - even stones.

80
00:07:36,115 --> 00:07:39,414
The quest for happiness
and the promotion of happiness--

81
00:07:40,419 --> 00:07:43,320
--is in all of this
and the power of our imagination.

82
00:07:45,625 --> 00:07:46,922
I'm writing a novel.

83
00:07:48,327 --> 00:07:51,455
I don't suppose you have the time
or the inclination to even read a novel.

84
00:07:52,264 --> 00:07:53,925
I've written one. It's going to be published.

85
00:07:54,767 --> 00:07:55,859
And I'm writing another.

86
00:07:56,502 --> 00:07:58,834
Can I read it?

87
00:07:59,705 --> 00:08:01,764
No-one has read It -- None of my friends.

88
00:08:03,676 --> 00:08:04,665
What's it about?

89
00:08:05,478 --> 00:08:07,912
About? It has something for everyone.

90
00:08:08,481 --> 00:08:10,142
A bit like Shakespeare?

91
00:08:10,182 --> 00:08:11,171
Perhaps, yes.

92
00:08:12,218 --> 00:08:14,413
Please don't talk to anyone about it.

93
00:08:15,054 --> 00:08:17,045
No. Course not.

94
00:08:17,123 --> 00:08:18,112
I won't tell a soul.

95
00:08:26,599 --> 00:08:29,625
Every human soul has seen,
perhaps even before their birth...

96
00:08:32,104 --> 00:08:36,541
... pure forms. Such as justice, temperance...

97
00:08:37,777 --> 00:08:38,869
... beauty ...

98
00:08:39,278 --> 00:08:41,610
... and all the great moral qualities
which we hold in honour.

99
00:08:43,082 --> 00:08:44,606
We are moved towards what is good...

100
00:08:45,384 --> 00:08:46,942
... by the faint memory of these forms.

101
00:08:48,621 --> 00:08:51,351
Simple - -and calm and blessed...

102
00:08:52,792 --> 00:08:55,386
...which we saw once in a pure clear light...

103
00:08:56,662 --> 00:08:57,890
... being pure ourselves.

104
00:09:04,170 --> 00:09:07,537
'Wholegrain'.
Do we have wholegrain or something other?

105
00:09:08,140 --> 00:09:10,938
What is whole?
Is It something in itself or does it have parts?

106
00:09:11,277 --> 00:09:12,266
Oh, spaghetti.

107
00:09:13,412 --> 00:09:14,504
If you have a whole you have a whole.

108
00:09:14,547 --> 00:09:15,536
Ooh, sausages.

109
00:09:16,415 --> 00:09:17,439
You and me is a whole.

110
00:09:17,817 --> 00:09:20,183
If you toddle off there's a hole in the whole.
Or, if I do.

111
00:09:20,920 --> 00:09:23,184
But a whole can't be broken,
it just forms another whole.

112
00:09:23,422 --> 00:09:24,411
-Baked beans.
-Baked beans.

113
00:09:25,391 --> 00:09:27,120
Do you want Premium points?

114
00:09:27,593 --> 00:09:28,651
Do we deserve them?

115
00:09:28,828 --> 00:09:29,817
-Do you want bags?
-Bags, yes.

116
00:09:30,696 --> 00:09:33,859
You know, it's all around us,
people like you and me talking nonsense.

117
00:09:34,033 --> 00:09:35,022
I know, I know.

118
00:09:35,668 --> 00:09:36,657
Bag for life:

119
00:09:37,703 --> 00:09:39,637
-For life?
-That's what it says.

120
00:09:40,039 --> 00:09:41,597
We have to ask, give you the choice.

121
00:09:42,374 --> 00:09:43,398
Ooh, rather.

122
00:09:44,410 --> 00:09:45,809
You just have to listen, that's the job.

123
00:09:46,245 --> 00:09:49,373
You call it a job but it's like music, what you do.

124
00:09:50,282 --> 00:09:53,809
You live with the angels,
speak their language, the music of the spheres.

125
00:09:55,221 --> 00:09:57,849
Nowadays the only language
anyone really understands...

126
00:09:58,257 --> 00:10:00,122
...is pictures. Paint the picture.

127
00:10:02,328 --> 00:10:04,296
See, now I'm bagged for life.

128
00:10:06,265 --> 00:10:08,096
Love's the only language everyone understands.

129
00:10:08,968 --> 00:10:10,026
Ooh love, yes.

130
00:10:10,402 --> 00:10:12,029
I can read It but I can't speak it.

131
00:10:20,880 --> 00:10:23,314
My coat's caught on your chair.

132
00:10:33,359 --> 00:10:36,328
And the captain said
as the two weevils dropped out of the biscuit...

133
00:10:36,796 --> 00:10:38,320
..."which would you rather have, Mr Smith?"

134
00:10:38,798 --> 00:10:39,787
"The bigger one, sir."

135
00:10:40,399 --> 00:10:43,630
"Wrong, Mr Smith, wrong."
"In the Navy you should always...

136
00:10:43,969 --> 00:10:44,958
...choose the lesser of the two weevils."

137
00:10:45,571 --> 00:10:46,560
Patrick O'Brian.

138
00:10:46,939 --> 00:10:49,203
"Between two evils
always choose the one you haven't tried before."

139
00:10:50,009 --> 00:10:51,738
Mea West. Oh my vest!

140
00:10:52,311 --> 00:10:53,710
I tore my vest again this morning.

141
00:10:53,946 --> 00:10:54,935
You must get some new vests.

142
00:10:55,414 --> 00:10:56,574
Jolly good.

143
00:10:57,650 --> 00:10:59,049
You must get some new vests.

144
00:11:00,186 --> 00:11:01,175
I just said that.

145
00:11:03,756 --> 00:11:06,088
You're always saying
that you just said something. Me too.

146
00:11:07,026 --> 00:11:09,221
Good job
you reminded me I had two lectures today.

147
00:11:09,829 --> 00:11:10,818
You remembered.

148
00:11:11,463 --> 00:11:14,364
No, but I remembered
to apologise for the one I forgot.

149
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:15,389
They were very sweet about it.

150
00:11:16,368 --> 00:11:17,892
Glad not to have listen to you, I expect.

151
00:11:18,304 --> 00:11:19,293
Oh, I'm sure.

152
00:11:20,372 --> 00:11:21,805
They'd have been delighted
to have listened to you.

153
00:11:22,942 --> 00:11:24,102
I always have been.

154
00:11:34,920 --> 00:11:36,444
-Iris!
-John.

155
00:11:39,358 --> 00:11:41,349
Than kyou. Keep the change.

156
00:11:42,061 --> 00:11:44,359
-Janet. Janet!
-Oh my God, Iris.

157
00:11:45,831 --> 00:11:46,820
Am I late?

158
00:11:48,033 --> 00:11:50,797
Oh no, it's the hokie-cokie.
Everything will be over.

159
00:11:51,403 --> 00:11:56,067
Oh, John, wait. I've got my stocking caught up.

160
00:11:56,842 --> 00:11:59,140
Stupid things. Really.

161
00:12:11,590 --> 00:12:14,218
I'm not sure I'm entirely -- I'm so sorry.

162
00:12:16,028 --> 00:12:17,017
Oh, sorry.

163
00:12:20,199 --> 00:12:21,188
Cha-cha-cha.

164
00:12:28,474 --> 00:12:29,463
Cha-cha-cha.

165
00:12:33,445 --> 00:12:34,605
-Thank you.
-You too.

166
00:12:37,883 --> 00:12:39,214
That was my husband.

167
00:12:42,121 --> 00:12:43,110
Cha-cha-cha.

168
00:12:46,158 --> 00:12:47,648
Are you with Iris?

169
00:12:48,794 --> 00:12:49,954
Hoping so.

170
00:12:50,629 --> 00:12:52,062
You know we have...

171
00:12:52,097 --> 00:12:53,086
I thought we had.

172
00:12:53,132 --> 00:12:54,121
...nearly met.

173
00:12:54,533 --> 00:12:56,364
-Are you a friend of Iris?
-Yes.

174
00:12:57,069 --> 00:12:59,299
She seems to have a lot of f...

175
00:12:59,772 --> 00:13:06,610
Janet Stone. John Bayley.

176
00:13:07,246 --> 00:13:08,713
-How do you do?
-How do you do?

177
00:13:09,348 --> 00:13:10,781
Shall we?

178
00:13:10,950 --> 00:13:11,939
What are your rooms like?

179
00:13:12,518 --> 00:13:13,610
Adequate,thank you.

180
00:13:14,420 --> 00:13:15,978
I'd like to see them.

181
00:13:19,692 --> 00:13:21,990
Do you have a lot of friends?

182
00:13:22,394 --> 00:13:23,861
Is a list of my friends necessary?

183
00:13:24,263 --> 00:13:26,060
I justwondered if you had many.

184
00:13:26,665 --> 00:13:28,690
There aren't many people
that one wants to know one.

185
00:13:30,703 --> 00:13:32,694
Iris!

186
00:13:40,079 --> 00:13:41,068
You might fall.

187
00:13:42,147 --> 00:13:43,409
Would you like some champagne?

188
00:13:43,849 --> 00:13:44,838
That would be nice.

189
00:13:45,117 --> 00:13:47,881
I've had some since Christmas...
It does keep, doesn't it?

190
00:13:56,528 --> 00:13:58,928
I shouldn't be doing this.

191
00:13:59,365 --> 00:14:00,297
What?

192
00:14:00,733 --> 00:14:03,201
Having women in my room. It's not permitted.

193
00:14:04,036 --> 00:14:05,367
I wouldn't say you'd had me exactly.

194
00:14:06,605 --> 00:14:11,474
Have you danced before?

195
00:14:13,078 --> 00:14:14,238
It was all right, wasn't it?

196
00:14:15,381 --> 00:14:16,541
Oh, I think so.

197
00:14:16,982 --> 00:14:19,109
Broke the ice, so to speak.

198
00:14:19,385 --> 00:14:20,374
-"Ice"?
-What?

199
00:14:22,254 --> 00:14:23,949
It'll do.

200
00:14:24,890 --> 00:14:27,154
Aren't you particular
about words at your college?

201
00:14:27,693 --> 00:14:31,652
I'm only here under sufferance really,
as a tutor and guide.

202
00:14:32,431 --> 00:14:34,956
I get all the Americans
and Frenchmen to mother.

203
00:14:37,002 --> 00:14:38,469
You love words, don't you?

204
00:14:39,638 --> 00:14:41,037
If one doesn't have words, how does one think?

205
00:14:45,010 --> 00:14:46,409
Shall I do that?

206
00:14:47,613 --> 00:14:50,377
What is your novel about?

207
00:14:51,183 --> 00:14:52,650
About?

208
00:14:54,386 --> 00:14:55,375
How to be free.

209
00:14:56,055 --> 00:14:57,044
How to be good...

210
00:14:59,558 --> 00:15:00,718
...and how to love.

211
00:15:01,994 --> 00:15:03,689
Well, that's all there is, I'd say.

212
00:15:07,232 --> 00:15:09,826
Language is all very well, you know, but...

213
00:15:10,202 --> 00:15:12,363
...it's not the only way
of understanding each other.

214
00:15:13,906 --> 00:15:14,895
There's sight and...

215
00:15:15,307 --> 00:15:17,775
...and smell and...touch, of course.

216
00:15:23,015 --> 00:15:24,209
I love your nose.

217
00:15:26,418 --> 00:15:27,476
It's snub.

218
00:15:37,262 --> 00:15:38,251
Snubby...

219
00:15:38,831 --> 00:15:40,162
...snubby, snubby.

220
00:15:42,935 --> 00:15:44,527
it's snubby, snubby, snubby.

221
00:16:06,792 --> 00:16:07,781
Let me do that to you.

222
00:16:09,261 --> 00:16:10,250
Take off your jacket.

223
00:16:33,986 --> 00:16:37,046
If we were, as it were, married...

224
00:16:37,389 --> 00:16:38,651
...we could do this all the time.

225
00:16:39,391 --> 00:16:40,380
Perhaps?

226
00:16:42,127 --> 00:16:43,890
We should be doing it nearly all the time.

227
00:16:44,196 --> 00:16:45,754
Yes, but if...

228
00:16:51,603 --> 00:16:54,071
Thank you.

229
00:17:27,940 --> 00:17:28,929
Look.

230
00:17:39,184 --> 00:17:40,173
I'm stopping you working.

231
00:17:40,719 --> 00:17:41,981
Yes, well, I don't mind.

232
00:17:46,058 --> 00:17:47,525
How's it coming along?

233
00:17:48,694 --> 00:17:50,389
It's harder to write than all the others. Much.

234
00:17:51,163 --> 00:17:52,152
Have you noticed?

235
00:17:52,798 --> 00:17:57,167
Just that you've seemed...
puzzled every now and again.

236
00:17:57,903 --> 00:17:58,892
That's it, yes.

237
00:18:00,772 --> 00:18:01,898
Puzzled.

238
00:18:04,376 --> 00:18:09,678
Puzzled. It's a funny word.

239
00:18:10,983 --> 00:18:14,248
All words are like that
when you take them by surprise, aren't they?

240
00:18:16,321 --> 00:18:17,720
Have you got a title?

241
00:18:19,391 --> 00:18:20,722
'A lot of trees...

242
00:18:21,793 --> 00:18:23,021
...seem near.'

243
00:18:27,599 --> 00:18:28,588
We must stop it.

244
00:18:29,101 --> 00:18:30,090
What to do?

245
00:18:30,435 --> 00:18:34,064
The window, John, the window!
We must stop it.

246
00:18:35,073 --> 00:18:36,062
No. See...

247
00:18:36,942 --> 00:18:37,931
...it's gone.

248
00:18:46,718 --> 00:18:49,016
We all worry about going mad, don'twe?

249
00:18:51,823 --> 00:18:53,120
How would we know...

250
00:18:54,059 --> 00:18:55,924
...those of us who live in our minds anyway?

251
00:18:59,798 --> 00:19:01,265
Other people would tell us.

252
00:19:03,635 --> 00:19:04,624
Would they, John?

253
00:19:10,575 --> 00:19:12,509
I don't want to set the world...

254
00:19:13,111 --> 00:19:14,100
Sorry.

255
00:19:15,013 --> 00:19:19,950
...on fire.

256
00:19:20,419 --> 00:19:21,852
John Bayley.

257
00:19:40,025 --> 00:19:41,014
Haven't seen her for ages.

258
00:19:41,426 --> 00:19:43,326
Jolly good -- nice.

259
00:19:45,063 --> 00:19:46,963
Takes all sorts. Not that I ...

260
00:19:48,233 --> 00:19:50,428
...we're all men at St Anthony's.

261
00:19:51,302 --> 00:19:52,496
